<caption id="DF23663B5B69A9313B88337AFCF4FB04" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" startId="12.[151,250,1107,1129]" targetBox="[169,1420,203,1063]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B69A9313B88337AFCF4FB04" blockId="12.[151,1435,1107,1160]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313B88337AFEAEFBE4" bold="true" box="[151,298,1107,1129]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">FIGURE 2-1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5C4D305B69A9313A2C337AFDBBFBE5" authorityName="Bordoni" authorityYear="2013" box="[307,575,1107,1129]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megalinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hailuogouensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313A2C337AFDBBFBE5" box="[307,575,1107,1129]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Megalinus hailuogouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313957337DFD1FFBE5" bold="true" box="[584,667,1108,1129]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21B57DA5B69A9313957337DFD1FFBE5" box="[584,667,1108,1129]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
: A. male tergite VIII; B. male sternite VIII; C. male sternite IX; D. male tergite X; E. median lobe of aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bars 0.30 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B69A9313BD8339DFF45FB7D" blockId="12.[151,1437,1204,1949]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD8339DFE05FB41" bold="true" box="[199,385,1204,1229]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" reason="1">Mesoscutellum.</emphasis>
Shiny, extensively covered with polygonal reticulum, and with paired punctures on anterior 1/3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B69A9313BD833D5FE8FFA0C" blockId="12.[151,1437,1204,1949]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD833D5FE0DFA99" box="[199,393,1276,1301]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD833D5FE97FA99" bold="true" box="[199,275,1276,1301]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Elytra</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13672A365B69A9313A3D33D5FEF8FA99" box="[290,380,1276,1301]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,419,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-122@11.[151,1436,409,1778]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Forebody: A. Megalinus hailuogouensis sp. nov.; B. M. ningxiaensis sp. nov.; C. M. tangi sp. nov. Scale bars 0.30 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Subquadrated (EL to EW ratio 1.1), obviously wider than pronotum, but longer. Humeri well developed, lateral margins widened posteriorly, hind margin subtruncated. Integument shiny and flattened, without microsculpture; each elytron with 8–9 rows of medium-sized punctures; deflexed portion with 7–8 rows of punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B69A9313BD832A5FB19F9B9" blockId="12.[151,1437,1204,1949]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD832A5FEC6FA29" bold="true" box="[199,322,1420,1445]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" reason="1">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Cylindrical, broadest at segment VI. Tergites III–VII shiny, covered with superficial transverse microstriae and small setiferous punctures, interspaces between punctures near 2–3 punctures’ diameter, denser laterobasally; each tergite with basal impression, which impunctate, but bearing distinct polygonal reticulum. Surface between two basal transverse carinae impunctate, but bearing distinct transverse microstriae. All abdominal sternites shiny, with microsculpture and setiferous punctures as those on tergites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B69A9313BD83169FBBDF8F5" blockId="12.[151,1437,1204,1949]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD83169FE80F9D5" bold="true" box="[199,260,1600,1625]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Male</emphasis>
. Abdominal segment VIII entirely covered with setiferous punctures, except a narrow medial longitudinal impunctate band; posterior margins of tergite VIII slightly emarginated or subtruncated (
<figureCitation id="13672A365B69A9313E03314DFAE6F9F1" box="[1308,1378,1636,1661]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,419,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-122@11.[151,1436,409,1778]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Forebody: A. Megalinus hailuogouensis sp. nov.; B. M. ningxiaensis sp. nov.; C. M. tangi sp. nov. Scale bars 0.30 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
-1A), that of sternite VIII slightly protruding backwards (
<figureCitation id="13672A365B69A93139FA31A1FCA9F92D" box="[741,813,1672,1697]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,419,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-122@11.[151,1436,409,1778]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Forebody: A. Megalinus hailuogouensis sp. nov.; B. M. ningxiaensis sp. nov.; C. M. tangi sp. nov. Scale bars 0.30 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
-1B). Tergite IX symmetrical, connected mediobasally. Sternite IX asymmetrical, with gradually-sharpened base and broadly arcuate posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="13672A365B69A9313FD63185FA8BF949" box="[1225,1295,1708,1733]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,419,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-122@11.[151,1436,409,1778]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Forebody: A. Megalinus hailuogouensis sp. nov.; B. M. ningxiaensis sp. nov.; C. M. tangi sp. nov. Scale bars 0.30 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
-1C). Tergite X symmetrical and narrow, with slightly rounded base and subtruncated posterior margin, 
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313F8A31F8FB5FF964" box="[1173,1243,1745,1768]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">in situ</emphasis>
broadly exposed between tergite IX (
<figureCitation id="13672A365B69A9313A6031DDFE42F881" box="[383,454,1780,1805]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,419,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-122@11.[151,1436,409,1778]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Forebody: A. Megalinus hailuogouensis sp. nov.; B. M. ningxiaensis sp. nov.; C. M. tangi sp. nov. Scale bars 0.30 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
-1D). Median lobe of aedeagus elliptical, large sized (
<figureCitation id="13672A365B69A9313F2931DDFBF9F881" box="[1078,1149,1780,1805]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,419,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-122@11.[151,1436,409,1778]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Forebody: A. Megalinus hailuogouensis sp. nov.; B. M. ningxiaensis sp. nov.; C. M. tangi sp. nov. Scale bars 0.30 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
-1E), basal piece without transparent, membranous medial-longitudinal band, anterior portion subcylindrical, 
<quantity id="4CA49B565B69A9313F563031FB35F8BC" box="[1097,1201,1816,1841]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.23">0.23 mm</quantity>
; basal bulb 
<quantity id="4CA49B565B69A9313E273031FA18F8BC" box="[1336,1436,1816,1841]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.2" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.82">0.82 mm</quantity>
long. Parameres symmetrical, elongate, slightly longer than 1/3 of basal bulb. Internal sac with two rows of spines, left one more transverse and larger; basal part crossed and with dense small spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B69A9313BD830ADFE26F811" blockId="12.[151,1437,1204,1949]" box="[199,418,1924,1949]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD830ADFEA1F810" box="[199,293,1924,1949]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B69A9313BD830ADFE9AF811" bold="true" box="[199,286,1924,1949]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Female</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34665385B68A9303BD837BEFCF1FE0B" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B68A9303BD837BEFCF1FE0B" blockId="13.[151,1437,151,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B68A9303BD837BEFEBFFF3C" bold="true" box="[199,315,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species could be distinguished from its congeners by: 1) head subquadrated; 2) small, ellitpical, densely-distributed punctures between anteocular furrows; 3) posterior half of frontal furrows indistinct; 4) admedian row of pronotum consisting of 11–13 punctures and lateral row, curvedly arranged, of 12–13 punctures; 4) tergites III–VII covered with superficial transverse microstriae; 5) posterior margins of tergite VIII slightly emarginated or subtruncated; 6) tergite X symmetrical and narrow, with rounded base and broadly arcuate posterior margin; 7) median lobe of aedeagus rather oblong; 8) basal piece with transparent, membranous mediallongitudinal band; 9) internal sac S-shaped and densely spinulate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
